ğŸ‘‰ What Big-O Represents

Big-O notation describes how an algorithm scales as the input size n grows very large.
It focuses on the dominant term that grows fastest.
Constant factors donâ€™t change the growth rate, they only scale the work up or down.

ğŸ”¹ Example 1: Linear time
def f1(n):
    for i in range(n):
        print(i)

This does n operations â†’ O(n)

def f2(n):
    for i in range(100*n):
        print(i)

This does 100*n operations â†’ still O(n)

âœ… The 100 is just a constant factor â†’ doesnâ€™t change the growth rate as n â†’ âˆ

ğŸ”¹ Example 2: Quadratic vs Linear

O(nÂ²) vs O(100n) â†’ Even if n is small, O(nÂ²) eventually grows much faster than O(100n).
Thatâ€™s why Big-O ignores constants and focuses on the fastest-growing term.

ğŸ”¹ Intuition

Big-O = â€œhow the runtime grows as n grows very largeâ€
Constant multipliers only stretch or shrink the runtime, but the shape of growth stays the same.

ğŸ“Œ Analogy:

Think of a race track:

O(n) = straight path
O(nÂ²) = big hill

Multiplying by 10 is like adding a small slope â†’ doesnâ€™t change that the hill is still steeper than the straight path.

âœ… Summary:

Big-O ignores constants because we care about how the algorithm grows with n, not the exact number of operations.


ğŸ‘‰ Why base of a logarithm does not change the asymptotic complexity

ğŸ”¹ The Formula:

log_a n = (log_b n) / (log_b a)

a = old base
b = new base
n = the number we are taking log of

Meaning: you can convert a logarithm from one base to another by dividing by a constant log_b a.

Step by Step

Suppose we have log base 2 of n (log_2 n).
Using the formula:

log_2 n = log_10 n / log_10 2
log_10 2 â‰ˆ 0.301  # constant

So:
log_2 n â‰ˆ 3.32 * log_10 n                   # just a constant factor

ğŸ”¹ Why in Big-O it doesnâ€™t matter

Big-O notation ignores constant factors.
O(3.32 * log_10 n) = O(log n)

Similarly: O(log_2 n) = O(log_10 n) = O(ln n)

âœ… So the base of a logarithm does not change the asymptotic complexity.

Intuition
Whether you halve a list (log_2 n), divide by 10 (log_10 n), or divide by e (ln n), the number of steps grows very slowly compared to n.

The base only changes the scale by a constant, which Big-O ignores.